name: Bewick's Wren
location: Cottonwood Canyon, Pasadena, Los Angeles County, California
remarks:
Recorded in an east-facing canyon with a mixture of chaparral and canyon live oaks, California sycamore, eucalyptus, deodar, and non-native pines.

Equipment: Sony PCM-M10 recorder and a Sennheiser MKE-400 microphone.
Modifications to the file: none.

name: Bewick's Wren
location: Los Alamos, Los Alamos County, New Mexico
remarks:
This recording was extracted from a video taken with a Canon 7D Mk II DSLR camera using the internal mic.  The audio was processed using Adobe Audition's adaptive noise filter to knock down background hiss 15dB.  

The wren was sitting in a dead juniper singing for several minutes.  Each song was roughly the same, as evidenced by this recording.

name: Northern Mockingbird
location: East Moriches, New York, USA
remarks:
This unidentifyed fellow starts his call  mid june, around midnight and continues for hours, each night. The variety of different tones and songs seems endless. Each of the different variations continues for 8-10 seconds before moving on to the next. Is this bird imitating other birds they've heard? Or sounds like a car alarm? What's the function of this type of call? 

The bird was unseen, it's a costal environment, 100 meters from an ocean bay. seems like this was a lone bird. no other calls or action.

remarks: singing from exposed perches on top of dead cottonwoods; real Western Kingbirds seemed energized by imitations by the Mockingbird, and calmed down when it departed; first recording of this individual on this date

location: San Bernardino National Wildlife Refuge, Cochise County, Arizona

name: Northern Mockingbird
location: San Bernardino National Wildlife Refuge, Cochise County, Arizona
remarks: singing from an exposed perch on top of a tall hackberry, the tallest object around; did jump songs, up to 5m into the air, returning to the same perch, ending at 1:58, 2:31, 4:06, 5:11, 6:08; believed to be same bird as an earlier recording, now about 150m away from original spot, Western Kingbird now only as an imitation, no real kingbirds;

name: Northern Mockingbird
location: San Bernardino National Wildlife Refuge, Cochise County, Arizona
remarks: singing from high in mesquites, flew off a long way to chase another; starts with imitation of Mexican Jay!!! (not present within 50 km of this spot), also of Ash-throated Flycatcher, Cassin's Kingbird, and various question marks; 1st of 2 recordings of this individual

location: San Simon Cienega, Cochise County, Arizona
remarks: cont. counter-singing with No 2; moved four times in the first two minutes, getting farther away, interval shortened at 1:59, then in next segment, moved five times; Brown-crested Flycatcher at 4:05, among many; interval shortened at 5:00; good Western Kingbird at 5:40, ? Western Scrub-Jay a short while later; this is Individual No 3 as I was calling it today, the 2nd recording of it;

name: American Robin
location: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
remarks:
Natural sound. Bird perched 3/4 of the way up a large water oak on the grounds near the house. In the same vicinity as robin recorded recently using mimicked phrases within the same sort of plastic song, possibly same individual.

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 1kHz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

name: American Robin
location: Moose Brook, Coos Co., New Hampshire
remarks: natural vocalization; song type made up almost entirely of 'hissely' phrases, from a bird perched near the top of a tall decidious tree.  Halfway through the cut another Robin flew into the tree and worked its way up to the singing bird, at which point the singing bird lowered the volume of the song to the point it could be called whisper song.

name: Song Sparrow
location: Campton Forest Preserve, Kane County, Illinois
remarks: Perched approximately twenty feet above ground, occasionally preening. Includes two cuts: the first is a little under two minutes and was stopped short to reposition so I was not recording directly into the sun; the second begins with the first song version, and then switches to a different version. The last song is a third version, after which the bird dropped down and stopped singing.

This recording is of a Song Sparrow that sings 4 times.

The mystery is immediately after the first time it sings.
The next 3 times both birds sing at the same time so the song is superimposed.
It seems like the mystery bird is following the Song Sparrow song.

I guess it's another Song Sparrow with a different kind of song.

name: Song Sparrow
location: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
remarks:
Bird was perched 2-3 m above the ground near the top of an isolated box elder (Acer negundo) in an open grassland ~50m from a forest edge. I was only about 5-8 m from the bird and watched the bird through binoculars while recording because I could not see the bill opening. If the bill was opened at all, it was very slight, but the tail and plumage quivered during the vocalizations. Just after 1:34 a male Northern Cardinal chased the bird out of the tree briefly before the juvenile and a second Song Sparrow returned to chase away the Cardinal. After this the juvenile resumed singing while the second sparrow moved away into the grass. 

# Editing #
Adobe Audition FFT filter, 2048 pts, Blackman window, 1 kHz to 14 kHz bandpass.

name: Song Sparrow
location: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
remarks:
Perched in the top of a shrub singing. Possibly the background individual from the XC287998. Switches to a second song at 2:08.

#Editing#
FFT filter in Adobe Audition, Blackman window, 2048 pts, 400Hz-14kHz bandpass.

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

FFT filter in Adobe Audition, Blackman window, 2048 pts, 400Hz-14kHz bandpass.

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

name: Song Sparrow
location: Lake Bemidji State Park, Beltrami, Minnesota
remarks:
Singing from atop a small tree on the shore of a still-frozen lake. Another Song Sparrow counter-singing in the background. 

Recorded with Sennheiser ME66 from 10m away. Light filtering of low frequencies. 

Yellow-bellied Sapsucker (at e.g. 4:37 and following) almost seems to be responding to one particular song type whose introductory notes are superficially similar to the sapsucker's call.

name: Song Sparrow
location: Powderhorn Park, Minneapolis, Hennepin, Minnesota
remarks:
Second individual recorded today. Singing just before dawn from shoreline vegetation along a pond in an urban park.  After the first series of song (around 4:30), the focal bird flew into a deeper section of shoreline vegetation and appeared to chase another bird around.  Some wing noises and rustling vegetation can be heard.  After the altercation, one bird flew back out to a perch and resumed singing.  It may be the same bird or it may have been another bird.

Filtered low frequencies for urban noise.  Recorded with Olympus LS-10S and Sennheiser ME66.  Distance to microphone ~ 5m.

name: Song Sparrow
location: Battelle Darby Metro Park--Darby Dan Training Loop trail (SW corner)
remarks: White-eyed Vireo was singing/calling while gathering nesting material.  Song Sparrow song is somewhat atypical/uncommon (perhaps a hatch year bird?). Recording made using a Sennheiser ME67 shotgun mic (built-in bass roll-off filter was OFF) and a Sony Hi-MD recorder, model MZ-RH910. Audacity was used to crop and apply a high-pass filter to the recording. WAV available at http://soundcloud.com/paul-j-hurtado/white-eyed-vireo-part2-7june2012.  Other species observed in the area are listed in this eBird Checklist: http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S10955303

remarks: It was still dark when this was made.  It is a pleasure not to have the 'air' of commerce and traffic on this suburban island in the background. Other than applying 4dB of gain and fades at beginning and end, the recording is untouched. It was made with a Sennheiser MKH416 in a Rode B;limp into a Sound Devices 722.

location: Cave Creek Ranch, Portal, Cochise County, Arizona

name: Northern Cardinal
location: Tanglewood Lane, Cincinnati, Ohio
sound_type: Several different song types appear in this recording of part of a single bout.,
remarks:
Filtering: Bass roll-off from about 600 Hz

Habitat: Suburban yard; lawn, trees

Behavior: Adult (season, plumage) male (plumage). Song from 12 m. high perch on partially wooded hillside. Two other birds in the area sang similar song types and appear in background of this recoding. Individuals at this location generally have a repertoire of 9-11 song types and most or all of  these are shared with with other NoCa in the area.

name: Northern Cardinal
location: Oyster Creek Park, Sugar Land, Fort Bend County, Texas
remarks:
This is a really nice recording to listen to. It gives the impression that the individual with the principal voice in this recording talks to the other on the background, and the other answers him.

Important to stand out that this individual (as can be heard) sings the same song (arrangement of notes) three times and then changes to another one. After this three, the background Cardinal takes a little longer to start his song again and when he does then the principal individual jumps in the new arrangement of notes before he finished his "turn".

name: Northern Cardinal
location: Powderhorn Park, Minneapolis, Hennepin, Minnesota
remarks:
Singing just before dawn from 2m up in a lilac bush in an urban residential neighborhood.  Same territory as XC121457.  Another cardinal can be heard counter-singing in background. 

Recorded from about 10m distance, using homemade parabolic reflector and Olympus LS-10S.

location: Engel Conservation Area, Waukesha County, Wisconsin
remarks: complex song from male singing to nearby female who can be heard chipping. Note presence of whirring trills in between songs. The male extended his crest, lowered his tail and leaned strongly to one side, then the other as he sang. The female was in front of and slightly above the male.
